The paper discusses how software engineering can be adapted for Computational Science (CS) and uses quantitative evidence from Github to check 13 published beliefs about CS. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) and Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science (cs.CE) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the implications of limitations of computer hardware, which could place it in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper also discusses the cultural environment of scientific software development, which could place it in the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.MS) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the changing nature of CS software development, which could place it in the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category.
